               <p>224. <persName id="def1-224-18381126" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-224-18381126" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-224-18381126" type="age" value="50"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-224-18381126" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-224-18381126" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-224-18381126" type="occupation" value="clothier's servant"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SAMUEL BROOKS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18381126-224-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18381126-224-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18381126-224-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18381126-cd-188" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18381126-224-offence-1 t18381126-cd-188"></join>3rd of No<lb></lb>vember</rs>, three shirts, value 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 jacket, value 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 1 pair of breeches, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18381126-name-1336" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1336" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1336" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1336" type="given" value="LEWIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1336" type="occupation" value="wholesale clothier"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18381126-224-offence-1 t18381126-name-1336"></join>Lewis Davis</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18381126-name-1337" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1337" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1337" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1337" type="given" value="LEWIS"></interp>LEWIS DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a wholesale clothier, and live at Green's-end, Woolwich. The prisoner was four years in my service—I lost a quantity of articles, which I found in pledge—I employed a constable to search—(<hi rend="italic">looking at a note</hi>)—the pawnbroker showed me this note—it is the pri<lb></lb>soner's writing—when I supposed the prisoner was the thief I sent for him, and said to him, "I have missed a great quantity of these shirts; do you know any thing about it?"—he said, "No"—I said, "I am quite certain</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183811260216"></xptr>
               <p>there must be some unfair play here; have you had any one at the work-shop to-day who is likely to have taken any away?"—he said, "No"—I said, "What quantity of them have you*"—he said, "Not any"—I asked where he lived—he told me—I said, "I shall search, for I think you must know something of them"—he said he lived in Bray's-buildings—I said, "You have a lodging at Delagar's, the publican"—I called the office; and sent him with the prisoner to search the place.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18381126-name-1338" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1338" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1338" type="surname" value="CHITTENDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1338" type="given" value="WILLIAM THOMAS"></interp>WILLIAM THOMAS CHITTENDEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a constable of Woolwich. On the 17th of November I went with Mr. Davis to the Earl of Chatham public-house, and was shown a room there—I found a bundle containing two shirts—the prisoner was sent for to—I opened the bundle, and took out the shirts—the prisoner produced the key of another box in the room—I found there another shirt, and detained him—I found on him a duplicate for a jacket and breeches.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18381126-name-1339" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1339" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1339" type="surname" value="BIRT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1339" type="given" value="THOMAS PACY"></interp>THOMAS PACY BIRT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker, in Hare-street, Woolwich. I produce a jacket and breeches—I do not know who they were pawned by, but I gave the party this duplicate—this note was left with the things—I did not know the prisoner was constantly in the prosecutor's employ—I knew he was a tailor.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Note read</hi>.)—"Sir, please to lend on this fisher boy's suit 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. "<hi rend="smallCaps">SAMUEL BROOKS</hi>."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18381126-name-1340" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1340" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1340" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1340" type="given" value="LEWIS"></interp>LEWIS DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> These articles are mine—they are not made for sale, but for the Navy.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. I took them home to get a stain out of the one found in my box—the others I took home to get altered, which it was my duty to do—I had five suits of the clothes, and did pledge them, as I wanted money—I put the shirts on a chair when I took them home—the one stained was left with my wife to get the stain out, and I placed it in my box—the other two remained loose in the room for fire days—I did not secrete them—I was going to give them to a person to alter.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18381126-name-1341" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1341" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1341" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-name-1341" type="given" value="LEWIS"></interp>LEWIS DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> These are navy shirts—it was the prisoner's duty to receive them when made, and send a cheque round for payment——those which are not made right he was empowered to get altered—not to take to his private lodging, but to give them to work-people who came to the shop—his wife worked for us.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18381126-224-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18381126-224-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18381126-224-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="lesserOffence"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi> of stealing the jacket and breeches.—Aged 50.</p>
               <p>
